## Security Vulnerability Review

**Vulnerability Found: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) - Reflected/Stored**

- **CWE Number:** CWE-79 (Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation, 'Cross-site Scripting')
- **File and Line:** `comments.js`, line 4 (`div.innerHTML = "<b>" + comment.author + ":</b> " + comment.body;`)

**Explanation:**
The code directly interpolates `comment.author` and `comment.body` into the `innerHTML` of a newly created `<div>` element. Since these values originate from a server API (`/api/comments`), an attacker who can inject malicious content into the database (e.g., by submitting a comment with a script payload like `<script>alert('XSS')</script>` in either the author or body field) will have that script executed in the context of any user viewing the comments. This is a classic stored XSS vulnerability because the malicious payload is persisted on the server and served to multiple users.

**Concrete Fix:**
Avoid using `innerHTML` with unsanitized data. Instead, use `textContent` or create elements safely:

```javascript
function renderComment(comment) {
    const div = document.createElement("div");
    div.className = "comment";

    // Safely set the author part
    const authorSpan = document.createElement("b");
    authorSpan.textContent = comment.author;
    div.appendChild(authorSpan);

    // Add a colon separator
    const colon = document.createTextNode(": ");
    div.appendChild(colon);

    // Safely set the body part
    const bodySpan = document.createElement("span");
    bodySpan.textContent = comment.body;
    div.appendChild(bodySpan);

    document.getElementById("comments").appendChild(div);
}
```

By using `textContent`, any special characters in `comment.author` and `comment.body` are treated as plain text rather than HTML, preventing script injection.

