### 1. Format String Vulnerability
**(1) Vulnerability Class & CWE:** Format String Vulnerability (CWE-134)  
**(2) File & Line:** `util.c`, line 16 (`printf(name);`)  
**(3) Exploitability:** The `name` buffer is populated directly from user-controlled input `raw_name`. Passing it as the format string to `printf` allows an attacker to inject format specifiers. Specifiers like `%x` can leak sensitive stack data (information disclosure), while `%n` can write arbitrary values to memory, potentially leading to remote code execution.  
**(4) Concrete Fix:** Never pass user input directly as a format string. Use `%s` and ensure proper null-termination after truncation:
```c
