### 2. Integer Overflow Leading to Heap Buffer Overflow
**(1) Vulnerability Class & CWE:** Integer Overflow / Wraparound leading to Heap-based Buffer Overflow (CWE-190 → CWE-122)  
**(2) File & Line:** `util.c`, lines 6–7 (`malloc(n + 1);` and `memcpy(p, s, n);`)  
**(3) Exploitability:** If the caller passes `n == SIZE_MAX`, the expression `n + 1` wraps around to `0`. Depending on the allocator, `malloc(0)` may return a valid non-NULL pointer. The subsequent `memcpy(p, s, n)` will then copy `SIZE_MAX` bytes into that tiny allocation, corrupting heap metadata and adjacent memory regions. This can be leveraged to overwrite function pointers or control flow data for arbitrary code execution.  
**(4) Concrete Fix:** Validate the size parameter before allocation and check the allocator's return value:
```c
char *dup_n(const char *s, size_t n) {
    if (n == SIZE_MAX) return NULL; // Prevent wraparound
    char *p = malloc(n + 1);
    if (!p) return NULL;            // Check for allocation failure
    memcpy(p, s, n);
    p[n] = '\0';
    return p;
}
```

### 3. Unchecked Allocation Size & NULL Pointer Dereference
**(1) Vulnerability Class & CWE:** NULL Pointer Dereference & Integer Conversion Issue (CWE-476, CWE-190)  
**(2) File & Line:** `util.c`, lines 20–22 (`int len = atoi(len_hdr);` and `memcpy(buf, raw, len);`)  
